---
import BaseLayout from '../../layout/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/reports/model-showdown.css';
---
<BaseLayout
  pageTitle="Testing 49 LLMs Across 5 Dimensions for $4.63 — Model Showdown"
  description="Which model should you actually use? We tested 49 LLMs across reasoning, knowledge, instruction following, coding, and MCP tool use. Claude Sonnet 4.6 achieves 100% on 4 dimensions."
  category="studio"
  fullWidth
  bodyClass="bg-[#f8f6f1]"
>

<div class="report-scope">
<div class="container">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div class="hero">
    <div class="hero-label">Umwelten Model Showdown &middot; March 2026</div>
    <h1>Testing 49 LLMs Across<br><em>5 Dimensions</em> for $4.63</h1>
    <p class="hero-subtitle">
      Which model should you actually use? Not which one tops a leaderboard somewhere &mdash;
      which one will reason through your problem, follow your formatting instructions, write code
      that compiles, answer factual questions correctly, and orchestrate real-world tools without falling apart?
    </p>
    <div class="hero-meta">
      <span>49 models</span>
      <span>5 providers</span>
      <span>5 dimensions</span>
      <span>$4.63 total</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card s-green"><div class="stat-num">100.0%</div><div class="stat-label">Top Score</div></div>
    <div class="stat-card s-accent"><div class="stat-num">$0.01</div><div class="stat-label">Best Value</div></div>
    <div class="stat-card s-yellow"><div class="stat-num">11</div><div class="stat-label">Models &gt;95%</div></div>
    <div class="stat-card s-ink"><div class="stat-num">$4.63</div><div class="stat-label">Total Cost</div></div>
  </div>

  <!-- 01 — What We Tested -->
  <section>
    <div class="section-num">01 &mdash; What We Tested</div>
    <h2>Five dimensions, one question: how good is this model?</h2>
    <p class="body-text">
      Each dimension tests something the others can&rsquo;t. A model that aces reasoning might struggle with
      precise formatting. A coding specialist might fail at tool orchestration. The combined score reveals
      which models are genuinely well-rounded.
    </p>

    <div class="dim-grid">
      <div class="dim-card">
        <h4>Reasoning &mdash; /20</h4>
        <p>Four classic logic puzzles where the obvious answer is wrong, scored 1&ndash;5 each by an LLM judge
          on reasoning quality:</p>
        <ul class="dim-list">
          <li><strong>The Surgeon Riddle</strong> &mdash; &ldquo;The surgeon says &lsquo;I can&rsquo;t operate on
            this boy, he&rsquo;s my son.&rsquo; How is this possible?&rdquo;</li>
          <li><strong>Bat &amp; Ball</strong> &mdash; &ldquo;A bat and ball cost $1.10. The bat costs $1.00 more
            than the ball. How much does the ball cost?&rdquo; (Answer: $0.05, not $0.10)</li>
          <li><strong>Lily Pads</strong> &mdash; &ldquo;A patch doubles daily. It covers the lake in 48 days.
            When is it half-covered?&rdquo; (Answer: day 47)</li>
          <li><strong>Counterfeit Coin</strong> &mdash; Find a counterfeit coin among 12 using a balance scale
            exactly 3 times, and determine if it&rsquo;s heavier or lighter. The hardest task in the
            entire showdown.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="dim-card">
        <h4>Knowledge &mdash; /30</h4>
        <p>30 factual questions, binary scoring (correct or not) with an LLM judge that allows formatting
          variations. Six categories:</p>
        <ul class="dim-list">
          <li><strong>Science</strong> &mdash; Speed of light, glucose formula, Carbon-14 half-life,
            Oganesson atomic number, Schwarzschild radius</li>
          <li><strong>Geography</strong> &mdash; Capital of Kazakhstan, deepest ocean point, country
            with most time zones, longest African river, Caspian+Persian Gulf border</li>
          <li><strong>History</strong> &mdash; Berlin Wall year, first to South Pole, WWI treaty,
            transistor year, Principia Mathematica author</li>
          <li><strong>Technology</strong> &mdash; HTTPS port, max signed 32-bit int, HTTP/0.9 year,
            OSI Layer 4, what CUDA stands for</li>
          <li><strong>AI/ML</strong> &mdash; What &ldquo;T&rdquo; in GPT stands for, Transformer d_model,
            feed-forward activation, Llama creator, knowledge distillation</li>
          <li><strong>Tricky/Adversarial</strong> &mdash; R&rsquo;s in &ldquo;strawberry,&rdquo; is 91
            prime, &ldquo;all but 9 die,&rdquo; feathers vs steel, 3/5 gallon jug puzzle</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="dim-card">
        <h4>Instruction Following &mdash; /30</h4>
        <p>Six constraint tasks, deterministic scoring (5 points each, no LLM judge):</p>
        <ul class="dim-list">
          <li><strong>Exact Word Count</strong> &mdash; &ldquo;Write a 12-word sentence about the ocean.
            Nothing else.&rdquo;</li>
          <li><strong>Structured JSON</strong> &mdash; Output JSON with name, age (25&ndash;35), 3 skills,
            active=true. No markdown fences.</li>
          <li><strong>Constrained List</strong> &mdash; List 5 animals, numbered, max 8 chars each,
            alphabetical order, no extra text.</li>
          <li><strong>Negative Constraints</strong> &mdash; Describe a sunset without &ldquo;beautiful,&rdquo;
            &ldquo;sky,&rdquo; &ldquo;orange,&rdquo; or exclamation marks. Exactly 2 sentences.</li>
          <li><strong>Format Transformation</strong> &mdash; Convert CSV data (Alice/Bob/Charlie) to a
            markdown table with header and separator.</li>
          <li><strong>Multi-format Response</strong> &mdash; Three sections separated by &ldquo;---&rdquo;:
            a color word, a number 1&ndash;100, the color repeated 3&times;. No labels.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="dim-card">
        <h4>Coding &mdash; /126</h4>
        <p>Six challenges in TypeScript, Python, and Rust (7 points each &times; 18 = 126).
          Code is extracted, compiled, and run in Docker containers:</p>
        <ul class="dim-list">
          <li><strong>FizzBuzz Boom</strong> &mdash; Extended FizzBuzz with divisibility by 3, 5, and 7
            for numbers 1&ndash;105</li>
          <li><strong>Business Days</strong> &mdash; Count working days between dates, skipping weekends
            and 8 specific 2025 US holidays</li>
          <li><strong>Vending Machine</strong> &mdash; State machine processing 18 INSERT/SELECT operations
            with exact output format</li>
          <li><strong>Grid Paths</strong> &mdash; Dynamic programming: count unique paths on blocked grids
            (right/down only). Three grids: 5&times;5, 7&times;7, 10&times;10</li>
          <li><strong>Zigzag Cipher</strong> &mdash; Rail fence cipher encode and decode with 3&ndash;4 rails.
            4 test cases with exact expected output</li>
          <li><strong>Data Pipeline</strong> &mdash; Parse 13 sales records and compute total revenue, top
            region, top product, high-quantity count, and average revenue</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="dim-card" style="margin-top:1.5rem">
      <h4>MCP Tool Use &mdash; /16</h4>
      <p>Connect to TezLab&rsquo;s MCP server with 20+ real tools and analyze vehicle data.
        Scored on tool usage (0&ndash;6) plus LLM-judged response quality (0&ndash;10):</p>
      <ul class="dim-list">
        <li><strong>Required tools</strong> &mdash; <code>list_vehicles</code>, <code>get_battery_health</code>,
          <code>get_charges</code>/<code>get_charge_report</code>, <code>get_efficiency</code>,
          <code>get_my_chargers</code>, <code>search_public_chargers</code> (1 point each)</li>
        <li><strong>Quality scoring</strong> &mdash; Data synthesis (1&ndash;5), actionable insights (1&ndash;5),
          factual grounding with specific %, kWh, and dates from tool results</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>The 49 Models</h3>
    <div class="model-list">
      <h4>OpenRouter (31 models)</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6</li>
        <li>anthropic/claude-opus-4.6</li>
        <li>anthropic/claude-haiku-4.5</li>
        <li>openai/gpt-5.4</li>
        <li>openai/gpt-5.4-mini</li>
        <li>openai/gpt-5.4-nano</li>
        <li>openai/gpt-oss-20b</li>
        <li>openai/gpt-oss-120b</li>
        <li>x-ai/grok-4.20-beta</li>
        <li>x-ai/grok-4.1-fast</li>
        <li>google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview</li>
        <li>qwen/qwen3.5-397b-a17b</li>
        <li>qwen/qwen3.5-122b-a10b</li>
        <li>qwen/qwen3.5-35b-a3b</li>
        <li>deepseek/deepseek-v3.2</li>
        <li>meta-llama/llama-4-scout</li>
        <li>meta-llama/llama-4-maverick</li>
        <li>inception/mercury-2</li>
        <li>inception/mercury-coder</li>
        <li>moonshotai/kimi-k2</li>
        <li>moonshotai/kimi-k2.5</li>
        <li>minimax/minimax-m2.7</li>
        <li>minimax/minimax-01</li>
        <li>mistralai/mistral-small-2603</li>
        <li>mistralai/mistral-small-3.2-24b-instruct</li>
        <li>mistralai/codestral-2508</li>
        <li>mistralai/ministral-8b-2512</li>
        <li>nvidia/nemotron-3-nano-30b-a3b:free</li>
        <li>nvidia/nemotron-3-super-120b-a12b:free</li>
        <li>nvidia/nemotron-nano-9b-v2:free</li>
        <li>google/gemma-3-27b-it</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="model-list">
      <h4>Google (2 models)</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>gemini-3-flash-preview</li>
        <li>gemini-3.1-pro-preview</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="model-list">
      <h4>DeepInfra (3 models)</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>nvidia/Nemotron-3-Nano-30B-A3B</li>
        <li>nvidia/NVIDIA-Nemotron-3-Super-120B-A12B</li>
        <li>nvidia/NVIDIA-Nemotron-Nano-9B-v2</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="model-list">
      <h4>Ollama (13 models)</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>deepseek-r1-14b</li>
        <li>deepseek-r1-32b</li>
        <li>deepseek-r1-latest</li>
        <li>devstral-latest</li>
        <li>gemma3n-e4b</li>
        <li>glm-4.7-flash-latest</li>
        <li>gpt-oss-latest</li>
        <li>mistral-small-latest</li>
        <li>nemotron-3-nano-4b</li>
        <li>nemotron-3-nano-latest</li>
        <li>phi4-latest</li>
        <li>qwen3-30b-a3b</li>
        <li>qwen3-32b</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 02 — Overall Results -->
  <section>
    <div class="section-num">02 &mdash; Overall Results</div>
    <h2>Full leaderboard</h2>
    <p class="body-text">
      Combined score is the mean of normalized dimension percentages. <code>anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6</code>
      achieves a perfect 100% on 4 dimensions and 93.8% across all 5 including MCP. Models with MCP data
      use all 5 dimensions; those without use 4. <code>qwen/qwen3.5-397b-a17b</code> leads the 5-dimension
      leaderboard at 93.1%. 41 of 49 models now have full 5-dimension scores including MCP tool use.
    </p>
    <p class="body-text">Click any column header to sort. Use filters to narrow down by provider or cost tier.</p>

    <div class="table-controls">
      <input type="text" id="search" placeholder="Search models...">
      <button class="filter-btn active" data-f="all">All</button>
      <button class="filter-btn" data-f="openrouter">OpenRouter</button>
      <button class="filter-btn" data-f="google">Google</button>
      <button class="filter-btn" data-f="deepinfra">DeepInfra</button>
      <button class="filter-btn" data-f="ollama">Ollama</button>
      <button class="filter-btn" data-f="free">Free</button>
      <span class="filter-sep">|</span>
      <button class="filter-btn" data-f="open">Open Weights</button>
      <button class="filter-btn" data-f="closed">Closed</button>
    </div>
    <div class="range-filters">
      <div class="range-filter">
        <label>Min score</label>
        <input type="range" id="filter-score" min="0" max="90" value="0" step="5">
        <span class="range-val" id="filter-score-val">any</span>
      </div>
      <div class="range-filter">
        <label>Max cost</label>
        <input type="range" id="filter-cost" min="0" max="100" value="100">
        <span class="range-val" id="filter-cost-val">any</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="filter-summary" id="filter-summary"></div>

    <div class="results-table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr>
          <th data-sort="rank">#</th>
          <th data-sort="model">Model</th>
          <th data-sort="provider">Provider</th>
          <th data-sort="released">Released</th>
          <th data-sort="type">Type</th>
          <th data-sort="combined">Combined</th>
          <th data-sort="reasoning">Reason</th>
          <th data-sort="knowledge">Know</th>
          <th data-sort="instruction">Instr</th>
          <th data-sort="coding">Code</th>
          <th data-sort="mcp">MCP</th>
          <th data-sort="cost">Cost</th>
          <th data-sort="time">Time</th>
        </tr></thead>
        <tbody id="leaderboard-body"></tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

  </section>

  <!-- 03 — Biggest Surprises -->
  <section>
    <div class="section-num">03 &mdash; Biggest Surprises</div>
    <h2>What we didn&rsquo;t expect</h2>
    <div class="finding-grid">
      <div class="finding-card">
        <div class="f-num">#1</div>
        <h4>Claude Sonnet 4.6 achieves 100%</h4>
        <p>Perfect on all 4 dimensions: reasoning, knowledge, instruction, and coding. The only model
          in the entire 49-model field to do it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card">
        <div class="f-num">#2</div>
        <h4>GPT-OSS-120B costs a penny</h4>
        <p>At $0.01, <code>openai/gpt-oss-120b</code> scores 89.9% across all 5 dimensions. That&rsquo;s $0.01 for
          strong performance across every dimension including MCP tool use.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card">
        <div class="f-num">#3</div>
        <h4>Local models are competitive</h4>
        <p><code>gpt-oss:latest</code> on Ollama scores 77.2% across all 5 dimensions for free. 13 local
          models tested, several above 80%. You don&rsquo;t need an API key for strong results.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card">
        <div class="f-num">#4</div>
        <h4>11 models above 95%</h4>
        <p>The frontier is crowded. The gap between #1 (100%) and #11 (96.9%) is only 3.1 percentage
          points. Choosing between top models is now about cost and speed, not quality.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card">
        <div class="f-num">#5</div>
        <h4>qwen3-30b-a3b: brilliant and broken</h4>
        <p>Perfect 20/20 reasoning, perfect 126/126 coding, but only 4/30 on instruction following.
          A spectacular failure mode &mdash; it ignores formatting constraints entirely.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card">
        <div class="f-num">#6</div>
        <h4>Same weights, different results</h4>
        <p>Nemotron Nano 30B: OpenRouter 83.7% vs DeepInfra 77.0%. The provider gap can exceed 6
          percentage points. Benchmarks are provider-specific.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 04 — Deep Dive: Reasoning -->
  <section>
    <div class="section-num">04 &mdash; Deep Dive: Reasoning</div>
    <h2>The counterfeit coin problem</h2>
    <p class="body-text">
      The single hardest task in the entire showdown. You have 12 coins, one is counterfeit (heavier or
      lighter &mdash; you don&rsquo;t know which). Using a balance scale exactly 3 times, find the counterfeit
      coin and determine whether it&rsquo;s heavier or lighter. Three weighings give 27 possible outcomes for
      24 possible states &mdash; it&rsquo;s information-theoretically tight.
    </p>
    <p class="body-text">
      Many models failed this task. The failure pattern is consistent:
      models correctly identify the first step (divide into 3 groups of 4) but then hand-wave through the
      subcases with phrases like &ldquo;narrow it down to the suspect&rdquo; without proving that exactly 3
      weighings suffice for every branch.
    </p>

    <div class="question-block">
      <div class="q-label">Judge on Claude Haiku 4.5</div>
      <blockquote>
        &ldquo;The response correctly identifies that the puzzle is solvable in 3 weighings and attempts a
        reasonable initial strategy (divide into thirds, weigh 4 vs 4). However, the procedure is incomplete
        and contains critical gaps. Step 2 is vague and hand-wavy.&rdquo;
      </blockquote>
    </div>

    <h3>Counterfeit Coin Results</h3>
    <div class="results-table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr>
          <th>Result</th>
          <th>Models</th>
        </tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="tier-1">
            <td><strong style="color:var(--green)">Solved (5/5)</strong></td>
            <td class="model-cell" style="white-space:normal">
              All three Qwen 3.5 variants, gpt-oss-120b, kimi-k2, nemotron-nano:free (OR),
              mercury-2, Nemotron Super 120B (both providers), gemini-3-flash-preview
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="tier-4">
            <td><strong style="color:var(--red)">Failed (2/5)</strong></td>
            <td class="model-cell" style="white-space:normal">
              gpt-oss-20b, minimax-m2.7, deepseek-v3.2, both Llama 4 variants, mistral-small-3.2,
              mercury-coder, claude-haiku-4.5, Nemotron-Nano (DI), codestral-2508, gemma-3-27b-it,
              ministral-8b
            </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p class="body-text">
      What&rsquo;s striking is that <code>openai/gpt-oss-20b</code> &mdash; the best coding model in the
      showdown &mdash; falls on its face here. It can write correct code in three languages but can&rsquo;t
      reason through a logic puzzle requiring exhaustive case analysis. This is exactly why multi-dimensional
      evaluation matters.
    </p>

    <h3>The Cross-Provider Reasoning Gap</h3>
    <p class="body-text">
      <code>nvidia/nemotron-3-nano-30b-a3b:free</code> (OpenRouter) scored 20/20 but
      <code>nvidia/Nemotron-3-Nano-30B-A3B</code> (DeepInfra) only scored 17/20. Same weights.
      The DeepInfra variant failed the counterfeit coin (2/5) while OpenRouter solved it perfectly (5/5).
      Quantization or inference configuration can affect a model&rsquo;s ability to maintain long chains
      of reasoning.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- 05 — Deep Dive: Knowledge -->
  <section>
    <div class="section-num">05 &mdash; Deep Dive: Knowledge</div>
    <h2>What models get wrong</h2>
    <p class="body-text">
      Many models achieved a perfect 30/30. Those that missed questions each missed 1&ndash;5.
      The errors reveal how models process information.
    </p>

    <h3>&ldquo;How many R&rsquo;s in Strawberry?&rdquo;</h3>
    <p class="body-text">
      Three models answered &ldquo;2&rdquo; instead of &ldquo;3.&rdquo; Both Llama 4 variants and
      <code>mistralai/mistral-small-3.2-24b-instruct</code> failed this classic character-counting test.
      Models that tokenize the word rather than examining individual characters consistently get it wrong.
      Multiple models still fail it in March 2026.
    </p>

    <h3>&ldquo;All But 9 Die&rdquo;</h3>
    <p class="body-text">
      &ldquo;A farmer has 10 sheep. All but 9 die. How many sheep does the farmer have left?&rdquo;
      <code>mistralai/codestral-2508</code> and <code>mistralai/ministral-8b-2512</code> both answered
      &ldquo;8,&rdquo; misinterpreting &ldquo;all but 9&rdquo; as &ldquo;10 minus 9 = 1 dies, leaving&hellip;
      8?&rdquo; Both failing models are from Mistral, suggesting a shared training-data blind spot.
    </p>

    <h3>The Carbon-14 Ambiguity</h3>
    <p class="body-text">
      Four models got the Carbon-14 half-life wrong (correct: 5,730 years).
      <code>meta-llama/llama-4-scout</code>, <code>mistralai/codestral-2508</code>,
      <code>mistralai/ministral-8b-2512</code>, and <code>openai/gpt-oss-20b</code> all provided
      incorrect or imprecise answers. The hardest science question by error count.
    </p>

    <h3>AI/ML Gotchas</h3>
    <p class="body-text">
      <code>google/gemma-3-27b-it</code> said the &ldquo;T&rdquo; in GPT stands for
      &ldquo;Transformative&rdquo; instead of &ldquo;Transformer.&rdquo;
      <code>mistralai/ministral-8b-2512</code> said the original Transformer&rsquo;s d_model was 64
      instead of 512. <code>openai/gpt-oss-120b</code> returned an empty response for the activation
      function question. Surprising for models that are themselves transformers.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- 06 — Deep Dive: Instruction Following -->
  <section>
    <div class="section-num">06 &mdash; Deep Dive: Instruction Following</div>
    <h2>Do exactly what I ask</h2>
    <p class="body-text">
      Many models achieved a perfect 30/30. The failures are mechanical and revealing.
      This is the easiest dimension to ace &mdash; and the least predictive of real-world capability.
    </p>

    <h3>The Markdown Fence Epidemic</h3>
    <p class="body-text">
      The most systematic failure: &ldquo;markdown fence hallucination.&rdquo; When told to output raw
      JSON with no markdown fences, models wrap it in <code>```json ... ```</code> anyway. When told to
      output a markdown table, models double-wrap the markdown inside a <code>```markdown</code> block.
      <code>google/gemma-3-27b-it</code> and <code>mistralai/ministral-8b-2512</code> both lost points
      for this &mdash; a deep training bias toward code-fence formatting that overrides explicit instructions.
    </p>

    <h3>Word Counting Is Hard</h3>
    <p class="body-text">
      &ldquo;Write a 12-word sentence about the ocean. Nothing else.&rdquo; Seven models got this wrong.
      <code>mistralai/codestral-2508</code> wrote 6 words. <code>moonshotai/kimi-k2</code> wrote 10. Four
      models wrote 11 (off by 1). Models that reliably nail word counts tend to be the same ones that
      score well on reasoning &mdash; they actually count rather than estimate.
    </p>

    <h3>Instruction Following Doesn&rsquo;t Predict Tool Use</h3>
    <p class="body-text">
      The most counterintuitive finding: perfect instruction following (30/30) does <em>not</em> predict
      good MCP tool use. <code>anthropic/claude-haiku-4.5</code> and <code>nvidia/Nemotron-3-Nano-30B-A3B</code>
      (DeepInfra) both got 30/30 on instruction yet scored 2/16 on MCP. Meanwhile,
      <code>inception/mercury-2</code> scored only 25/30 on instruction but got 11/16 on MCP.
      Following rules is a different cognitive task than autonomously planning a multi-step tool chain.
      Instruction following tests <em>compliance</em>; MCP tests <em>initiative</em>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- 07 — Deep Dive: Coding -->
  <section>
    <div class="section-num">07 &mdash; Deep Dive: Coding</div>
    <h2>Code that actually runs</h2>
    <p class="body-text">
      The coding dimension has the widest score spread: 0/126 to 126/126. Multiple models now achieve
      perfect scores, while the cipher and pipeline challenges still separate the strong from the weak.
    </p>

    <h3>Cipher TypeScript Results</h3>
    <p class="body-text">
      Many models produced perfect cipher implementations. Click column headers to sort.
    </p>

    <div class="results-table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr>
          <th data-sort="c-model">Model</th>
          <th data-sort="c-score">Score</th>
          <th data-sort="c-time">Time</th>
        </tr></thead>
        <tbody id="cipher-body"></tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p class="body-text">
      <code>qwen/qwen3.5-122b-a10b</code>, the overall winner, only scored 2/7 on cipher-typescript.
      Meanwhile, <code>google/gemma-3-27b-it</code> &mdash; near last overall &mdash; got a perfect 7/7.
      Single challenges can invert rankings.
    </p>

    <h3>Why Some Models Score Zero</h3>
    <p class="body-text">
      Three distinct failure modes explain the zero scores on cipher and data pipeline challenges:
    </p>
    <div class="finding-grid" style="grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr 1fr">
      <div class="finding-card">
        <div class="f-num">Failure Mode 1</div>
        <h4>65k token reasoning loops</h4>
        <p><code>openai/gpt-oss-20b</code> and <code>nvidia/nemotron-3-nano-30b-a3b:free</code> generated
          exactly 65,536 completion tokens (OpenRouter&rsquo;s max) in 4&ndash;7 minutes &mdash; but returned
          <strong>empty content</strong>. The models were trapped in internal reasoning/thinking chains that
          consumed the entire token budget without producing visible output. For <code>gpt-oss-20b</code>
          this was transient &mdash; it solved cipher in Rust and Python perfectly in a later batch. The cached
          empty result persisted.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card">
        <div class="f-num">Failure Mode 2</div>
        <h4>Infinite verification loops</h4>
        <p><code>qwen/qwen3.5-122b-a10b</code> spent <strong>5 minutes</strong> generating 31,000 tokens of
          visible reasoning &mdash; manually verifying its cipher solution by re-tracing the same index
          calculation dozens of times in an infinite loop. The code extractor found only a partial function,
          not a complete program. Score: 2/7.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card">
        <div class="f-num">Failure Mode 3</div>
        <h4>Token-limit truncation</h4>
        <p><code>nvidia/NVIDIA-Nemotron-3-Super-120B-A12B</code> (DeepInfra) hit 16k tokens and its output was
          truncated mid-generation. Hardcoded data strings got corrupted (missing newlines between records).
          The code compiled but produced wrong output. Score: 0&ndash;5/7 depending on the challenge.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="body-text">
      The cached responses reveal a nuanced picture. For <code>nvidia/nemotron-3-nano-30b-a3b:free</code>,
      the empty responses were consistent across multiple challenges &mdash; its coding score of 63/126
      reflects genuine limitations. But for <code>openai/gpt-oss-20b</code>, the cipher-typescript zero
      was a <strong>transient failure</strong> from an overnight API call that got cached. It solved
      cipher-rust and cipher-python perfectly in later batches (18k tokens, 45 seconds). If the overnight
      run had succeeded, its already-highest coding score of 112/126 would be even higher.
      <code>qwen/qwen3.5-122b-a10b</code>&rsquo;s infinite verification loop, however, is a
      <strong>model behavior</strong> &mdash; reasoning-heavy models can get trapped in self-checking
      loops on algorithmic problems.
    </p>

    <h3>Rust Is the Hardest Language</h3>
    <div class="results-table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr>
          <th>Language</th>
          <th>Avg Score</th>
          <th>Compile Rate</th>
          <th>Perfect Rate</th>
        </tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>TypeScript</strong></td>
            <td class="score-cell">5.3/7</td>
            <td>92%</td>
            <td>78%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Python</strong></td>
            <td class="score-cell">5.1/7</td>
            <td>88%</td>
            <td>76%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Rust</strong></td>
            <td class="score-cell">4.3/7</td>
            <td>72%</td>
            <td>65%</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="body-text">
      Rust&rsquo;s lower success rate comes from its strict type system and ownership model. Models
      struggle with borrowing, lifetimes, and the borrow checker &mdash; generating code that looks
      correct but fails to compile. The gap between Rust and TypeScript is consistent across all
      challenge types.
    </p>

    <h3>Speed as Capability</h3>
    <p class="body-text">
      Speed remains a decisive factor. Multiple top models now achieve perfect 126/126, but
      the data pipeline and cipher challenges still separate fast from slow. Models that respond
      within seconds across all 18 tasks &mdash; spanning FizzBuzz, business days, vending machines,
      grid paths, ciphers, and data pipelines &mdash; consistently rank higher overall.
    </p>
  </section>

