    <h3>Seven Layers of Provider Difference</h3>
    <p class="body-text">
      There are at least seven layers where providers can introduce behavioral differences, even when
      serving identical model weights:
    </p>
    <ul class="inline-list">
      <li><strong>Quantization</strong> &mdash; DeepInfra typically runs FP8; OpenRouter routes to NVIDIA&rsquo;s
        own infrastructure which may use different precision. Affects long reasoning chains most.</li>
      <li><strong>SDK layers</strong> &mdash; OpenRouter uses a native Vercel AI SDK provider; DeepInfra uses
        a generic OpenAI-compatible adapter. Tool calling and response parsing differ.</li>
      <li><strong>Middleware</strong> &mdash; OpenRouter applies context compression, response healing
        (malformed JSON repair), and schema modification. DeepInfra passes requests directly.</li>
      <li><strong>Tool-calling implementation</strong> &mdash; How tools appear in context, how results are
        formatted, how the model signals tool calls. The most likely explanation for the MCP gap.</li>
      <li><strong>Default parameters</strong> &mdash; Providers may inject different defaults for temperature,
        top_p, repetition penalty.</li>
      <li><strong>Token usage reporting</strong> &mdash; DeepInfra streaming token counts may be less accurate,
        affecting cost reporting.</li>
      <li><strong>Reasoning effort</strong> &mdash; Different providers expose different parameter names for
        reasoning tokens, potentially allocating different &ldquo;thinking time.&rdquo;</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="body-text">
      The practical implication: <strong>benchmarks are provider-specific</strong>. A score obtained on
      OpenRouter doesn&rsquo;t transfer to DeepInfra, or vice versa. If your application relies on tool
      calling, provider choice matters more than model choice.
    </p>
